" srcset="https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands.jpg.webp 1200w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-300x201.jpg.webp 300w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-150x100.jpg.webp 150w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-768x514.jpg.webp 768w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-735x492.jpg.webp 735w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-335x224.jpg.webp 335w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-347x232.jpg.webp 347w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-520x348.jpg.webp 520w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-640x428.jpg.webp 640w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-960x642.jpg.webp 960w, https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands-1080x723.jpg.webp 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 760px) calc(100vw - 24px), 720px" data-pin-media="https://destinationlesstravel.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/A-hotel-on-an-island-in-the-San-Blas-Islands.jpg" id="mv-trellis-img-11" data-trellis-processed="1"><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">You don&rsquo;t need much, just the essentials!</figcaption></figure>



<p>When you&rsquo;re visiting the San Blas Islands, your philosophy should be: if you want it, you bring it.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>First things first, you&rsquo;ll need to bring your passport, because you&rsquo;ll need to present this as you enter the Guna Yala territory. No passport, no entry.&nbsp;</p>



<p>You&rsquo;ll also need to bring US dollars because there are no credit cards or ATMs on the San Blas Islands. Bring plenty of small denominations &ndash; you really can&rsquo;t ask for change from a $100 bill out here.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>US dollars are widely used in Panama, so you won&rsquo;t need to worry about exchanging money before you go. In fact, Panama actually doesn&rsquo;t print its own currency (the balboa).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Most tours include your food, but you&rsquo;ll usually still need the $22 USD entry fee to the Guna Yala territory, as well as cash to buy coconuts from the locals, beautiful handmade molas, and drinks. If you want to take photos with the Guna people, they&rsquo;ll usually charge a dollar per picture, too.&nbsp;</p>



<p>You&rsquo;ll spend a lot of your time on the San Blas Islands in the water, so make sure to bring swimwear and towels.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Electricity is generally limited, so you&rsquo;ll need a powerpack to charge your phone and some spare camera batteries. And if you have a GoPro, definitely bring that along.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>It&rsquo;s also a good idea to bring bug repellent since the San Blas Islands have a tropical climate and that means one thing: mosquitoes!&nbsp;</p>



<p>You also may want to bring a lightweight travel cocoon for sleeping if you&rsquo;re worried about clean bedding. It&rsquo;s pretty hot on the San Blas Islands, so a full-on sleeping bag is probably going to be too thick.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Bring plenty of sun protection, too. Waterproof, reef-friendly sunscreen is a must, ideally with an SPF of 30 or above. You&rsquo;ll also need sunglasses, a sun hat, and a light beach cover-up if you&rsquo;re prone to sunburn. It&rsquo;s not a bad idea to bring some aloe vera gel, either, in case you do burn.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Make sure that you&rsquo;ve got all of your necessary toiletries with you because getting hold of them once you&rsquo;re there is going to be pretty darn difficult. You don&rsquo;t want to get to San Blas and realize you forgot your saline solution or your toothbrush!&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Bring light clothing, such as shorts and cotton t-shirts. You should also pack a light rain jacket in case of a downpour and for wearing on boat trips as you may get splashed.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Usually, group meals are served at a set time, so you might want to bring a few snacks with you to tide you over in between, like cereal bars, chips, or cookies.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Last but not least, bring some basic medication with you.&nbsp;Even if you&rsquo;re not prone to seasickness, we recommend having it with you just in case &ndash; it never hurts to be prepared! There are several brands available but Dramamine is one of the most popular and effective.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Other handy basics to have include painkillers, anti-diarrhea tablets, and antihistamines in case of bug bites. You&rsquo;re no more likely to get sick in San Blas than you are anywhere else, but since there aren&rsquo;t really any pharmacies around, it&rsquo;s best to be prepared!&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



